WARNING - it's a long one
-
Well that was not how I wanted to end my 2019 competition season. It just wasn't meant to be. I was strong going into the competition and I felt good. Yes a I got a bronze medal snatch but not making a jerk meant no total and no Olympic qualification points.
-
2019 certainly didn't go the way I thought it was going to. I started the year expecting a simple year in terms of life but a chaotic one in terms of olympic qualification.
-
Reality is it was chaotic in every direction. Start of May I found out my Mum had been diagnosed with cancer again. At the end of May, 10 days before an Olympic qualifying event, my fiancÃ© called off the relationship and our wedding because he found somebody else while he was away studying for a year and I was holding fort back home. I somehow then still pulled out a PB total performance 10 days later. Most people wouldn't even have turned up to the competition. After that the reality hit me and the wheels fell off. My body weight plummeted and my motivation to do weightlifting was none existent. I almost quit the game completely.
-
Then 5 weeks in the USA got me back on track and my performance at Worlds wasnt great but it was satisfactory in terms of my Olympic rankings.
-
Last month would have been when I was supposed to get married then and at the same time I realise someone who was once a best friend was stabbing me in the back.
-
Once I get home next week I'm moving house. It's taken me 6 months to work out where I'm going to live. What I'm going to do in terms of my training. (My ex used to write my programme and be my coach so doing weightlifting without him has been a whole new experience in itself). Basically it's taken me a little while to get back on track and feeling half like myself again.
I'm ready to get settled in my new life and start 2020 as I intend for it to go on. Refreshed, strong and ready for face the world head on. There are only so many times you can put on a brave face and hide behind the mask. It's draining constantly putting on an act that everything is ok when the world you have known for so long is falling down around you.

These photos from @weightlifting_house show the many faces that accompany a national record lift. What they don't show are the mental battle I was dealing with away from the bar. They don't show the tears that came for the days before. They don't show the heartache. They don't show the fear of the unknown.â 
-â 
I had a lot of my plate in the last 2 weeks building up to this competition but that platform was my safe place. The only thing I could control in my life at that time was my training and my performance. Many people wouldn't have even shown up on that day. But that attitude is the one that will one day make me achieve all my goals.â 
-â 
On reflection now, I think this competition saved me from a hard downward spiral as it kept my eyes on the prize.â 
